Looks like you&#39;re trying to implement the autocomplete functionality. Unfortunately, `datalist` does not include any kind of `id` attribute for an `option`. It only gives a list of pre-defined options for an `input`. You could set an attribute on the options and use the value from the `input` to get the attribute value from the DOM, but it would be better to just get the value using JavaScript instead.

From the template, send the `input` reference instead of the `option` (This step is not required if you are using `ngModel` or `formControl`)
```html
&lt;form (ngSubmit)=&quot;logMessageId(message)&quot;&gt;
    &lt;input class=&#39;form-control&#39; list=&quot;equipment_name_list&quot; name=&#39;equipment_name&#39; #message&gt;
    &lt;datalist name=&quot;equipment_name_list&quot; id=&quot;equipment_name_list&quot;&gt;
        &lt;option *ngFor=&quot;let message of messages&quot; [value]=&quot;message.text&quot;&gt;&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;/datalist&gt;

    &lt;button&gt;Send&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
```

Then in your component fetch the value from the list using [find][1].
```js
logMessageId(el){
    const message = el.value; // Use the ngModel or formControl value here instead if used
    const selectedMessage = this.messages.find(m =&gt; m.text === message);
    const messageId = (selectedMessage &amp;&amp; selectedMessage.id) || message; // Use the message entered by the user if the not selected from the list
    console.log(&quot;Message Id: &quot;, messageId);
}
```

You can also consider checking out Angular Material&#39;s [autocomplete][2] component.


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/find
  [2]: https://material.angular.io/components/autocomplete/examples

