The way i would do it is instead of listing all the files you want to load. load all the files in that path. put them into a map `Map&lt;String, BufferedImage&gt; textures = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();`  then you create the key from the file name. you can then generate and add the dark textures, adding &#39;dark_&#39; or &#39;d&#39; to the `Key`. then in get texture all you need to do is `if (darken) textures.get(&#39;d&#39;+name) else textures.get(name)`  
once all the textures are loaded from files here is something to get the dark versions

    textures.putAll(textures.entrySet().stream().collect(Collectors.toMap(entry-&gt;&quot;d&quot;+entry.getKey(),entry-&gt;darken(entry.getValue()))));

You want a [Map](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html).

A common (probably the most common) implementation of Map is [HashMap](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/util/HashMap.html):

    private static final Map&lt;String, Map&lt;Boolean, BufferedImage&gt;&gt; textures;

    static {
        String[] baseNames = {
            &quot;unknown&quot;,
            &quot;stone&quot;,
            &quot;grass&quot;,
            &quot;dirt&quot;,
            &quot;iron_ore&quot;,
            &quot;coal_ore&quot;,
            &quot;diamond_ore&quot;,
            &quot;bedrock&quot;,
            &quot;andesite&quot;,
            &quot;granite&quot;,
            &quot;marble&quot;,
        };

        Map&lt;String, Map&lt;Boolean, BufferedImage&gt;&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
        for (String baseName : baseNames) {
            BufferedImage regular =
                renderer.loadImage(path + baseName + &quot;.png&quot;);
            BufferedImage dark = darken(regular);

            Map&lt;Boolean, BufferedImage&gt; regularAndDark = new HashMap&lt;&gt;(2);
            regularAndDark.put(false, regular);
            regularAndDark.put(true, dark);

            map.put(baseName, Collections.unmodifiableMap(regularAndDark));
        }

        textures = Collections.unmodifiableMap(map);
    }

    /** returns the textures of the name provided */
    public static BufferedImage getTexture(String name, boolean darken) {
        Map&lt;Boolean, BufferedImage&gt;&gt; matches = textures.get(name);
        assert matches != null : &quot;No textures for name \&quot;&quot; + name + &quot;\&quot;&quot;;
        return matches.get(darken);
    }

However… there is room for improvement:

* As you can see, I added an `assert` statement to make sure no invalid string arguments are provided.  This can be avoided by using an `enum` value as an image key instead of a String, removing the possibility of misspellings.
* `Map&lt;Boolean, BufferedImage&gt;&gt;` is a little hard to follow.  I would make a simple inner class to hold both, so the structure is more obvious.

With that in mind, it looks like this:

    public enum TextureType {
        UNKNOWN,
        STONE,
        GRASS,
        DIRT,
        IRON_ORE,
        COAL_ORE,
        DIAMOND_ORE,
        BEDROCK,
        ANDESITE,
        GRANITE,
        MARBLE,
    }

    private static class Textures {
        final BufferedImage regular;
        final BufferedImage dark;

        Textures(BufferedImage regular) {
            this.regular = Objects.requireNonNull(regular,
                &quot;Image cannot be null&quot;);
            this.dark = darken(regular);
        }
    }

    private static final Map&lt;TextureType, Textures&gt; textures;

    static {
        Map&lt;TextureType, Textures&gt; map = new EnumMap(TextureType.class);
        for (TextureType type : TextureType.values()) {
            map.put(type,
                new Textures(renderer.loadImage(path + baseName + &quot;.png&quot;)));
        }

        textures = Collections.unmodifiableMap(map);
    }

    /** returns the textures of the name provided */
    public static BufferedImage getTexture(TextureType type, boolean darken) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(type, &quot;Texture type cannot be null&quot;);
        Textures match = textures.get(type);
        return darken ? match.dark : match.regular;
